ame <i>Manning</i>.","North German and Dutch: habitational name from a farm so named, once in possession of a certain <i>Manno</i> (see   Mann   2) and his kin."],"variants":[{"name":"Mannen","meanings":["Altered form of Irish or English   Manning  ."]},{"name":"Mannion","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Malachy, Brendan, Aislinn, Brigid, Ciaran, Declan, Dermot, Kieran, Liam, Maeve, Siobhan.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Mainnín</b> (see   Manning  ).","English and Irish: variant of   Mangan  ."]},{"name":"Mangan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Ciaran, Declan.","Irish: from <b>Ó Maingín</b>, see   Mannion  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Mongáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Mongán</i>’, a byname for someone with a luxuriant head of hair (from <i>mong</i> ‘hair, mane’)."]},{"name":"Mannings","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Donovan, Eamonn, Ronan.","Irish: variant of   Manning   1, with the addition of English excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Walter Manning was born in 1165, in Durham, Durham, England, United Kingdom, his father, Simon De Manning x[end], was 35 and his mother, Elgida, was -2. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs. Sarah Manning. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1165–":"1165–Surnud","1165–Male":"1165–S